       <div class="mrow">
        <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">LL</span>
       </div>
       <span class="mi">A</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">&lt;</span>
      <span class="mn">0</span>
     </div>
    </div>
    <span xlink:href="10640_2018_231_Article_IEq36.gif" class="inline-graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   </div>
  </div> and 
  <div id="IEq37" class="inline-formula">
   <div class="alternatives">
    <span id="M89" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ V_{LK}^{A} &gt; 0. $$\end{document}</span>
    <div id="M90" class="math">
     <div class="mrow">
      <div class="msubsup">
       <span class="mi">V</span>
       <div class="mrow">
        <span mathvariant="italic" class="mi">LK</span>
       </div>
       <span class="mi">A</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">&gt;</span>
      <span class="mn">0</span>
      <span class="mo">.</span>
     </div>
    </div>
    <span xlink:href="10640_2018_231_Article_IEq37.gif" class="inline-graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   </div>
  </div> The share of adaptation capital 
  <span class="italic">L</span> is zero if the net effect of a lower shock 
  <span class="italic">Π</span>(
  <span class="italic">L</span>) and a lower productive capital 
  <span class="italic">K</span>–
  <span class="italic">L</span> after the event cannot be positive. Otherwise, (
  <a rid="Equ15" ref-type="" href="#Equ15">15</a>) requires that the expected marginal return on adaptation capital in final goods units must be equal to the marginal productivity of capital used in production. The optimal amount of adaptation capital then increases in both capital and carbon stocks:
  <div id="Equ16" class="disp-formula">
   <span class="label">16</span>
   <div class="alternatives">
    <span id="M91" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$ L = L(P,K){\text{ with }}L_{P} &gt; 0{\text{ and }}L_{K} &gt; 0. $$\end{document}</span>
    <div id="M92" display="block" class="math">
     <div class="mrow">
      <span class="mi">L</span>
      <span class="mo">=</span>
      <span class="mi">L</span>
      <div class="mrow">
       <span stretchy="false" class="mo">(</span>
       <span class="mi">P</span>
       <span class="mo">,</span>
       <span class="mi">K</span>
       <span stretchy="false" class="mo">)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="mrow">
       <span width="0.333333em" class="mspace"/>
       <span class="mtext">with</span>
       <span width="0.333333em" class="mspace"/>
      </div>
      <div class="msub">
       <span class="mi">L</span>
       <span class="mi">P</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">&gt;</span>
      <span class="mn">0</span>
      <div class="mrow">
       <span width="0.333333em" class="mspace"/>
       <span class="mtext">and</span>
       <span width="0.333333em" class="mspace"/>
      </div>
      <div class="msub">
       <span class="mi">L</span>
       <span class="mi">K</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">&gt;</span>
      <span class="mn">0</span>
      <span class="mo">.</span>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div xlink:href="10640_2018_231_Article_Equ16.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
